{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure is at module handoff (collectors -> report-input builder), not a single pure function. REAL-INFRA: no real OS/network requirement to catch this; in-process fakes for the three sources can reproduce missing-source wiring bugs. MOCK-HIDE: unit-only tests of a merge helper could miss orchestration bugs where one collector is never invoked or dropped before handoff. LLM-DEP: disqualified by behavior text focusing on content passed into generation, not model output quality. MULTI-STEP: no multi-agent sequence. ADVERSARIAL-CRITIQUE: if the implementation is a single pure assembler function, Unit could be enough; however behavior text explicitly requires retrieved data from three source modules, so boundary interaction is the real failure surface. REJECTION-GATE: rejected System because behavior does not require real HTTP/subprocess/filesystem; rejected Agentic because it does not evaluate generated narrative correctness.","test_description":"Wire the real orchestrator + input-builder modules with three deterministic source stubs returning distinct sentinel fields. Run one report cycle and assert the payload sent to summary generation contains all three sentinel datasets and source provenance markers.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure appears when collector errors propagate through orchestrator/rendering fallback logic. REAL-INFRA: real network outage is not required; a stub source raising timeout/5xx can trigger the same branch. MOCK-HIDE: pure unit tests on formatter alone could pass while orchestration still aborts on exceptions. LLM-DEP: behavior is fallback control-flow and section annotation, not model judgment quality. MULTI-STEP: no chained agentic decisions required. INTEGRATION-BRAKE checks: (a) no required real OS/network, (b) no dependence on real AI output, (c) no multi-agent chain. ADVERSARIAL-CRITIQUE: if outage handling depends on real HTTP client exception types, System might be needed; behavior text says 'unavailable' generically and does not constrain transport-specific semantics.","test_description":"Use real orchestration/report assembly modules, with two healthy source stubs and one failing stub. Assert run completes, report contains the unavailable note only for the failed section, and process does not abort.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: correctness depends on what the real summary model generates from inputs (factual inclusion/faithfulness), which is non-deterministic and quality-based. A deterministic stub would always pass and hide hallucination/omission failures (deterministic-assertion trap). MOCK-MISS: integration wiring alone cannot detect semantic misrepresentation. REAL-INFRA: external API transport is secondary; the core failure boundary is model output quality. MULTI-STEP: single model generation step, so not Workflow. ADVERSARIAL-CRITIQUE: if summary generation is purely template-based, Integration could suffice; behavior wording 'narrative summary accurately represents' implies semantic generation quality, so Agentic remains the safer minimum. REJECTION-GATE: rejected Workflow because only one agentic decision is specified, not a sequence of agentic stages.","test_description":"Run the real summary-generation model against a fixed evaluation set of input datasets with known key values, and score outputs for factual inclusion/consistency (e.g., required-value extraction checks + human/LLM-as-judge spot checks) across repeated runs to catch stochastic misrepresentation.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: this behavior explicitly requires real delivery to an inbox, which depends on real network/email service behavior beyond in-process fakes. MOCK-HIDE: mocked SMTP/API can pass while auth, TLS, provider acceptance, or inbox routing fails in reality. LLM-DEP: although generation may exist in path, this behavior’s pass condition is transport/delivery correctness, not model output quality; agentic content quality is out of scope here. MULTI-STEP: no required sequence of multiple model decisions. ADVERSARIAL-CRITIQUE: if team uses a local mail sink as canonical inbox, Integration might be enough; behavior text says recipient inbox correctly, implying real end recipient path.","test_description":"Execute the script in an environment with reachable real source endpoints (or staging equivalents) and real email provider credentials to a test recipient mailbox. Assert a single report email is received in that inbox with expected subject/metadata and attached/body report content shape.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.18,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure is cross-module state handoff (generation -> persistence -> next-run retry queue). REAL-INFRA: can be reproduced with local filesystem and a failing mail client stub; no real network or OS scheduler required if next run is simulated by second invocation. MOCK-HIDE: unit tests of retry helper can miss persisted-state wiring between runs. LLM-DEP: no dependence on model output quality; only retry/fallback mechanics. MULTI-STEP: not an agentic pipeline. INTEGRATION-BRAKE checks: (a) no mandatory real OS/network beyond local file I/O, (b) no AI-output dependence, (c) no multi-agent chain. ADVERSARIAL-CRITIQUE: if retry semantics depend on real cron timing or provider-specific transient error codes, System could be required; behavior text only requires retry on next scheduled run, which can be emulated by two controlled runs.","test_description":"Run cycle 1 with a failing email adapter and real local persistence path; assert report file is written with retry metadata. Run cycle 2 with email adapter restored; assert queued report is sent and local pending artifact is cleared/marked delivered.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.64,"System":0.22,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
